Hash maps store key-value pairs in an array and use a **hash function** to turn each key into an array index. On lookup, the key is hashed, the index is computed, and the map checks only the small bucket or slot at that location instead of scanning everything. That’s why lookup is **average-case O(1)**: with a good hash function and a low load factor, keys are spread out evenly, so each lookup touches only a constant amount of work.

Worst-case lookup can degrade to **O(n)** if many keys collide into the same bucket, but in practice resizing and good hashing keep collisions rare.

```js
function countWordFrequencies(text) {
  const counts = new Map();

  const words = text
    .toLowerCase()
    .match(/\b[\w']+\b/g) ?? [];

  for (const word of words) {
    counts.set(word, (counts.get(word) || 0) + 1);
  }

  return counts;
}
```

Example:

```js
const result = countWordFrequencies("Hello world, hello friend! World.");
console.log(result);
// Map(3) { 'hello' => 2, 'world' => 2, 'friend' => 1 }
```

