555.answer:
Memoization stores the results of expensive function calls and reuses them when the same inputs appear again. In recursive algorithms, this avoids recomputing the same subproblems over and over.

For Fibonacci, the naive recursive version recalculates values like `fib(3)` and `fib(4)` many times, giving exponential time complexity `O(2^n)`. With memoization, each `fib(k)` is computed once, then looked up from cache afterward, reducing the time complexity to `O(n)`.

```js
function fib(n, memo = {}) {
  if (n in memo) return memo[n];
  if (n <= 1) return n;

  memo[n] = fib(n - 1, memo) + fib(n - 2, memo);
  return memo[n];
}

console.log(fib(10)); // 55
```

