576.answer:
A trie is a tree-based data structure for storing strings by shared prefixes.

- Each edge represents a character.
- Each node represents a prefix.
- A flag on a node marks whether that prefix is also a complete word.

Example for `cat`, `car`, `dog`:

```text
root
 ├─ c
 │   └─ a
 │       ├─ t*   => "cat"
 │       └─ r*   => "car"
 └─ d
     └─ o
         └─ g*   => "dog"
```

`*` means “this node ends a full word”.

## What problems it solves

A trie is useful when you need fast prefix-based string operations.

It helps with:
- **Prefix lookup**: quickly check whether any word starts with a prefix like `app`
- **Dictionary membership**: check whether a word exists
- **Autocomplete**: find words starting with typed characters
- **Spell checking / suggestions**: organize words by prefix
- **Word games**: Boggle, crossword helpers, etc.
- **Routing / pattern matching** in some systems

## Why use a trie instead of a hash set?

A hash set is great for exact lookup, but it does **not naturally support prefix queries**.

- Hash set `search("apple")`: fast
- Hash set `startsWith("app")`: not naturally efficient
- Trie `search("apple")`: fast
- Trie `startsWith("app")`: also fast

## Time complexity

Let `L` be the length of the word/prefix.

- `insert(word)`: **O(L)**
- `search(word)`: **O(L)**
- `startsWith(prefix)`: **O(L)**

This is efficient because work depends on the length of the input string, not the number of stored words.

## JavaScript implementation

```js
class TrieNode {
  constructor() {
    this.children = new Map();
    this.isEndOfWord = false;
  }
}

class Trie {
  constructor() {
    this.root = new TrieNode();
  }

  insert(word) {
    let node = this.root;

    for (const char of word) {
      if (!node.children.has(char)) {
        node.children.set(char, new TrieNode());
      }
      node = node.children.get(char);
    }

    node.isEndOfWord = true;
  }

  search(word) {
    let node = this.root;

    for (const char of word) {
      if (!node.children.has(char)) {
        return false;
      }
      node = node.children.get(char);
    }

    return node.isEndOfWord;
  }

  startsWith(prefix) {
    let node = this.root;

    for (const char of prefix) {
      if (!node.children.has(char)) {
        return false;
      }
      node = node.children.get(char);
    }

    return true;
  }
}

// Example usage
const trie = new Trie();
trie.insert("apple");

console.log(trie.search("apple"));   // true
console.log(trie.search("app"));     // false
console.log(trie.startsWith("app")); // true

trie.insert("app");
console.log(trie.search("app"));     // true
```

